## Using AI Assistants (optional)

This vault includes a `.claude/` scaffold that teaches AI coding agents how to work with your world.

To use it, open the vault directory in an AI coding agent such as [Claude Code](https://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/claude-code), Codex, or OpenCode. The agent automatically picks up:

- **Skills** in `.claude/skills/` -Obsidian conventions, Grimoire's three-layer model, and your project-specific canon rules
- **Commands** in `.claude/commands/` -worldbuilding workflows you can run

### Recommended Workflow

1. **Open your agent** in this vault's directory. It reads `CLAUDE.md` automatically and understands the three-layer model.
{% if include_sources %}2. **Ingest source material.** If you have an `.epub`, run `./scripts/split-epub.sh book.epub chapters` to split it into chapter files (requires `pandoc`: `brew install pandoc`). Otherwise, drop source files into `sources/chapters/` (or `wiki/`, `fragments/`) manually. Then run `/ingest-source` for each one. The agent extracts entities into `world/` with proper frontmatter and wikilinks.
3. **Check quality regularly.** After every 10-20 ingested entities, run `/lint-canon` to catch missing properties and canon inconsistencies. Once you have substantial canon, run `/audit-conflicts` to surface contradictions across entries.{% else %}2. **Create entities.** Use the templates (Ctrl/Cmd+T) or ask the agent to create notes for you. All entities live in `world/`.
3. **Check quality regularly.** After building up content, run `/lint-canon` to catch missing properties and `/audit-conflicts` to surface contradictions.{% endif %}
4. **Browse your world** using the Bases views in `views/` or from `home.md`.
5. **Iterate.** Add more sources, create original content, let the agent link entities together. The vault grows richer with each pass.

